observations.recommendation:
Fast track and continue the conduct of a complete physical count of all PPEs to accurately ascertain their actual existence and determine proper valuation of the same;

In coordination with MA, follow the procedural guidelines provided under Commission on Audit (COA) Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 for One-Time Cleansing of PPE accounts for non-existing/missing PPEs to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability; and

Ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded and that the Property and Ledger Cards are reconciled.

The Municipal Mayor direct the Inventory Committee to complete the conduct of the physical inventory of the Municipality’s PPE and submit to the Audit Team the properly accomplished RPCPPE;

The RPCPPE shall be reconciled with the accounting records in order to ensure that the PPE account balances are fairly presented in the financial statements. The discrepancies should be investigated and necessary adjustments should be made to come up with a complete and accurate balance of PPE accounts in the financial statements;

The Accounting Office should religiously maintain the PPELC to provide a detailed information of the PPE which can be of great importance in the conduct of the physical inventory;

The Property Custodian of the Municipality maintain Property Cards and provide/attach property sticker to each PPE item for ease of reference and property tagging;

Management give considerable time and additional personnel to work on the reconciliation of the physical count with the accounting records and the subsequent inventory tagging of all PPE and assignment of property codes for a more facilitative identification and tracking of the location of the properties.  Inventory Tag should be attached to the newly acquired equipment before these are distributed to the intended end-users;

A Municipal Valuation Committee be created to determine the appraised value of donated properties and those properties found on station during the inventory taking so that these properties can be correctly recorded in the books of accounts of the Municipality; 

Management consider the creation of a General Services Office (GSO) who will handle the receipt, issuance and recording of the procured and issued supplies and property; and

Henceforth, inventory taking and reconciliation of related subsidiary records should be regularly undertaken and regarded with utmost importance.

The Local Chief Executive (LCE) require the coordination between the Municipal Accountant and the designated General Services Officer towards the full implementation of the perpetual inventory method in the recording of all Inventory Accounts to ensure proper accounting and promote better control in the receipt and issuance of supplies and materials;

The Municipal Accountant and designated General Services Officer maintain the prescribed ledger cards and stock cards, respectively, for each type of Inventory, keep track the actual Supplies Inventory on hand and reconcile the balances of the two inventory records;

The LCE require the concerned personnel to conduct periodic physical inventory of supplies and materials which shall be reported in the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) and submitted to the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively.

We recommended the following:

The Municipal Mayor reconstitute a new Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical count of inventories semestrally, submit the RPCI and coordinate closely with the Municipal Accountant for the effective and efficient monitoring of inventories;

The Municipal Mayor set up a stockroom where inventories will be delivered and stored prior to issuance to end-users;


The Municipal Accountant apply consistently the perpetual inventory method in accounting for supplies and materials inventories;


The Municipal Accountant use the SSMI as basis for drawing the JEV to recognize the issuances or the corresponding supplies and materials expenses;


The Municipal Accountant maintain SLCs for all types of inventories;


The General Services Officer – Designate summarize the RIS, prepare the SSMI and submit to the Municipal Accountant to serve as basis in accounting for the issuances of supplies and materials; and

The General Services Officer – Designate maintain SC for all types of inventories.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the:
1. Municipal Accountant to:
a. Strictly observe the perpetual inventory method in the recording of purchases and issuance of supplies and materials;
b. Maintain Supplies Ledger Cards for each item for costing and reconciliation with the records of the GSO; and
c. Reconcile the results of the physical count of inventories with the accounting records;
2. GSO to:
a. Coordinate with the Municipal Accountant in the adoption of the perpetual inventory method in accounting for supplies and materials; and
b. Maintain stock cards for supplies and materials and reconcile the balance per stock with the ledger cards maintained by the MAO;
3. Inventory Committee to regularly conduct inventory counts of supplies and materials to facilitate the preparation of the Report on the Physical Count of Inventory (RPCI), and submit the said reports by July 31 and January 31 of each year.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Municipal Accounting Office, in close coordination with the Municipal Treasurer’s Office, immediately:
Establish and record RPT and SET Receivables at the beginning of each year, in accordance with NGAS and accrual accounting principles;
Recognize the corresponding Deferred Income for future collections;
Reconcile Accounting records with the Treasury Office’s Delinquency Report to address the ₱46.813 million discrepancy;
Institutionalize regular inter-office reconciliation and documentation procedures, including timely submission of updated RPTAR and certified taxpayer lists; and
Implement corrective accounting entries to reflect the true financial position and prevent recurrence of similar misstatements.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Municipal Accounting Office:
Review and correct the classification of interest expenses and borrowing costs in compliance with applicable accounting standards;
Adjust the Financial Statements to reclassify prior year interest and recognize the appropriate interest expense and capitalizable borrowing costs for CY 2024;
Recognize the accrued interest expense of ₱0.900 million as of December 31, 2024, to ensure liabilities are fairly stated; and
Implement a system for regular reconciliation between loan amortization schedules and general ledger records to avoid future misstatements.

Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with MA, make representation with the debtors by sending Demand Letters to settle their obligations and exert all possible remedies to collect the amount due to the Municipality;

MA prepare aging of all dormant receivables to support the request for write-off in accordance with Section 7.4 of the COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016; and

LCE consider filing the request for authority to write-off dormant receivable accounts to the COA.

Ensure compliance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 94-013 on the prompt return of unused balances to the SAs;

Hasten the implementation of the partially and unimplemented PPAs to maximize their intended benefits; and 

Monitor project timelines and ensure adherence to the reportorial requirements for fund liquidation within the prescribed period.

Require the GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) to increase the allocation for GPB to a minimum of five per cent of the Annual Budget;

Direct the GFPS and all concerned implementing units to maximize the utilization of the GAD Funds; and

Require the GFPS to apply the HGDG tool in the evaluation and assessment of the Agency’s accomplishments.

Maximize LDRRMF utilization focusing on PPAs requiring the highest priority in terms of urgency and/or impact on the four thematic areas of Disaster Risk Reduction and Management;

Ensure efficient and effective implementation of all programmed and reprogrammed projects during the budget year to optimize the fund’s utilization and warrant that goals and objectives of reducing disaster risk and enhancing disaster preparedness and response capabilities be achieved; and

Prospectively, in coordination with the Municipal Accounting Office and Municipal Budget Office, review and reconcile the status of utilization of PPAs to ensure accurate and reliable information presented in the submitted reports.

